04082nam a22005055i 9780674250031DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742500317 a10.4159/97806742500312doi  a(DE-B1597)567538  a(OCoLC)1189768464  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQB843.N4bM67 2020 7aSCI0040002bisacsh04a523.8/8742231 aMoskvitch, Katia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNeutron Stars /cKatia Moskvitch. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- t1. A Collision That Shook the Cosmos -- t2. Discovering Neutron Stars ... and Little Green Men? -- t3. When Stars Go Boom -- t4. Zombies and Starquakes -- t5. Journey to the Center of a Neutron Star -- t6. How Neutron Stars Keep Spoiling Dark Matter Theories -- t7. When Pulsars Have Planets -- t8. Giant Scientific Tools of the Universe -- t9. Fast Radio Bursts, an Unfinished Chapter -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe astonishing science of neutron stars and the stories of the scientists who study them.Neutron stars are as bewildering as they are elusive. The remnants of exploded stellar giants, they are tiny, merely twenty kilometers across, and incredibly dense. One teaspoon of a neutron star would weigh several million tons. They can spin up to a thousand times per second, they possess the strongest magnetic fields known in nature, and they may be the source of the most powerful explosions in the universe. Through vivid storytelling and on-site reporting from observatories all over the world, Neutron Stars offers an engaging account of these still-mysterious objects.Award-winning science journalist Katia Moskvitch takes readers from the vast Atacama Desert to the arid plains of South Africa to visit the magnificent radio telescopes and brilliant scientists responsible for our knowledge of neutron stars. She recounts the exhilarating discoveries, frustrating disappointments, and heated controversies of the past several decades and explains cutting-edge research into such phenomena as colliding neutron stars and fast radio bursts: extremely powerful but ultra-short flashes in space that scientists are still struggling to understand. She also shows how neutron stars have advanced our broader understanding of the universe—shedding light on topics such as dark matter, black holes, general relativity, and the origins of heavy elements like gold and platinum—and how we might one day use these cosmic beacons to guide interstellar travel.With clarity and passion, Moskvitch describes what we are learning at the boundaries of astronomy, where stars have life beyond death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aNeutron stars. 0aPulsars. 7aSCIENCE / Astronomy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067425003140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674250031423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674250031.jpg  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles